ng parenthesis ')'</b>:</p><ul><li><p>First, check if there are any <b>unma=
tched open parentheses</b>.</p></li><li><p>If the <code>unmatched open pare=
ntheses</code> counter is <b>greater than 0</b>, it means this closing pare=
nthesis has a match. Decrement the <code>unmatched open parentheses</code> =
counter.</p></li><li><p>If the <code>unmatched open parentheses</code> coun=
ter is <b>0</b>, it means this closing parenthesis is an <b>unmatched one</=
b>. To make the string valid, we must add an opening parenthesis to match i=
t. So, increment the <b>parentheses to add</b> counter.</p></li></ul></li><=
/ul></li><li><p><b>Final count:</b> After iterating through the entire stri=
ng, the <code>unmatched open parentheses</code> counter will hold the numbe=
r of opening parentheses that never found a matching closing parenthesis. T=
hese are also parentheses that must be added to make the string valid. So, =
add the value of the <code>unmatched open parentheses</code> counter to the=
 <code>parentheses to add</code> counter. The final sum is the minimum numb=
er of parentheses required to make the string valid.</p></li></ol><p>Let's =
