p><h2><b>Delete Center element</b></h2><p></p><p>This problem asks you to d=
elete the middle element of a stack <b>without using any additional data st=
ructures</b>. The input consists of an integer <code>N</code> representing =
the number of elements, followed by <code>N</code> integers that will be pu=
shed onto the stack. The final output should be the stack elements after th=
e middle element is deleted.</p><p>To solve this, we can use a <b>recursive=
 approach</b> that leverages the function call stack itself, as the problem=
's constraint is to avoid "additional" data structures like a temporary arr=
ay or another stack.</p><hr><p></p><h3><b>Logic and Algorithm</b></h3><p></=
p><p>The key is to recursively pop elements from the stack until we reach t=
he middle element. Once we reach the middle, we simply don't push that elem=
ent back.</p><ol start=3D"1"><li><p><b>Find the middle position:</b> The mi=
ddle index of a stack with <code>N</code> elements is <code>N/2</code>. Sin=
ce stack indices are 0-based and the bottom is at index 0, the middle eleme=
nt is at <code>N/2</code> (for odd <code>N</code>) or at <code>N/2-1</code>=
 (for even <code>N</code>) from the bottom.</p></li><li><p><b>Recursive Fun=
ction:</b> Create a recursive function, say <code>deleteMiddle(stack, curre=
nt_size, middle_index)</code>, that takes the stack, its current size, and =
the calculated middle index as arguments.</p><ul><li><p><b>Base Case:</b> T=
he recursion stops when the current size of the stack is equal to the middl=
e index. At this point, the element at the top is the middle element.</p></=
li><li><p><b>Recursive Step:</b></p><ul><li><p>Pop the top element from the=
 stack and store it in a temporary variable.</p></li><li><p>Recursively cal=
l the <code>deleteMiddle</code> function on the remaining stack.</p></li><l=
i><p>Once the recursive call returns (meaning the middle element has been h=
andled), push the stored element back onto the stack.</p></li></ul></li></u=
l></li><li><p><b>Handling the Middle Element:</b> When the function reaches=
 the middle element (based on the <code>current_size =3D=3D middle_index</c=
ode> condition), it simply pops it and does not push it back, effectively d=
eleting it.</p></li><li><p><b>Final Output:</b> After the initial call to t=
he recursive function returns, the stack will contain all elements except t=
he middle one. You can then print the elements in the desired order (from t=
op to bottom).</p></li></ol><hr><p></p><h3><b>C Implementation</b></h3><p><=
/p><p>The C code below demonstrates this approach. It uses a stack implemen=
tation with a simple array and a <code>top</code> pointer. The <code>delete=
Middle</code> function is recursive and follows the logic described above.<=
