ade-animation-function: linear;"><p></p><h2><b>Infix to Postfix Conversion<=
/b></h2><p></p><p>To convert an infix expression to a postfix expression, y=
ou can use a <b>stack</b> to manage operators based on their precedence and=
 the presence of parentheses. The core principle of the algorithm is to pro=
cess the infix string from left to right and append operands directly to th=
e result, while using a stack to handle operators and parentheses.</p><p></=
p><h3><b>Algorithm</b></h3><p></p><ol start=3D"1"><li><p>Initialize an empt=
y <b>stack</b> for operators and an empty string or character array for the=
 <b>postfix expression</b>.</p></li><li><p>Iterate through the <b>infix exp=
ression</b> character by character.</p></li><li><p>For each character:</p><=
ul><li><p><b>Operand (A-Z):</b> If the character is an operand, append it d=
irectly to the postfix expression.</p></li><li><p><b>Opening Parenthesis '(=
':</b> Push it onto the operator stack.</p></li><li><p><b>Closing Parenthes=
is ')':</b> Pop operators from the stack and append them to the postfix exp=
ression until an opening parenthesis <code>(</code> is found. Discard both =
the opening and closing parentheses.</p></li><li><p><b>Operator (+, -, *, /=
, ^):</b> Pop operators from the stack and append them to the postfix expre=
ssion as long as the stack is not empty, the top of the stack is not an ope=
ning parenthesis, and the precedence of the stack's top operator is greater=
 than or equal to the current operator's precedence. After this, push the c=
urrent operator onto the stack.</p></li></ul></li><li><p>After the loop fin=
ishes, pop any remaining operators from the stack and append them to the po=
stfix expression.</p></li></ol><p></p><h3><b>Precedence Rules</b></h3><p></=
p><p>Operator precedence is crucial for this algorithm. Operators with high=
er precedence are evaluated first.</p><ul><li><p><code>^</code> (power) has=
 the highest precedence.</p></li><li><p><code>*</code>, <code>/</code> have=
 the next highest precedence.</p></li><li><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>=
 have the lowest precedence.</p></li><li><p>The associativity for <code>^</=
code> is right-to-left. For all other operators, it's left-to-right.</p></l=
i></ul><p>To implement this, you can define a helper function <code>precede=
nce(char operator)</code> that returns an integer value representing the op=
erator's priority. For example, <code>^</code> can return <code>3</code>, <=
code>*</code> and <code>/</code> can return <code>2</code>, and <code>+</co=
de> and <code>-</code> can return <code>1</code>. Parentheses can be handle=
d separately.</p><hr><p></p><h3><b>C Implementation</b></h3><p></p><respons=
