e>top2</code> to track the top of each stack.</p><ul><li><p><code>top1</cod=
e> starts at -1, representing an empty stack1.</p></li><li><p><code>top2</c=
ode> starts at <code>size</code>, representing an empty stack2.</p></li></u=
l></li><li><p><b><code>push1(int x)</code>:</b></p><ul><li><p>Before pushin=
g, check for <b>overflow</b>. Overflow occurs if <code>top1</code> and <cod=
e>top2</code> are adjacent, meaning <code>top1</code> is equal to <code>top=
2 - 1</code>. If it is, print "Overflow of stack1".</p></li><li><p>If there=
's no overflow, increment <code>top1</code> and then place the element <cod=
e>x</code> at <code>array[top1]</code>.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b><code>p=
ush2(int x)</code>:</b></p><ul><li><p>Before pushing, check for <b>overflow=
</b>. Overflow occurs if <code>top2</code> and <code>top1</code> are adjace=
nt, meaning <code>top2</code> is equal to <code>top1 + 1</code>. If it is, =
print "Overflow of stack2".</p></li><li><p>If there's no overflow, decremen=
t <code>top2</code> and then place the element <code>x</code> at <code>arra=
y[top2]</code>.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b><code>pop1()</code>:</b></p><ul=
><li><p>Check for <b>underflow</b>. Underflow occurs if <code>top1</code> i=
s -1. If it is, print "Underflow for stack1" and return an appropriate valu=
e like -1.</p></li><li><p>If there's no underflow, store the element at <co=
de>array[top1]</code>, decrement <code>top1</code>, and then return the sto=
red element.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b><code>pop2()</code>:</b></p><ul><l=
i><p>Check for <b>underflow</b>. Underflow occurs if <code>top2</code> is e=
qual to the total size of the array. If it is, print "Underflow for stack2"=
 and return -1.</p></li><li><p>If there's no underflow, store the element a=
